Origin of Species. Drawing on his own ambitious research in Darwin’s manuscripts and at the Beagle’s remotest ports of call, Sponsel takes us from the ocean to the Origin and beyond. He provides a vivid new picture of Darwin’s career as a voyaging naturalist and metropolitan author, and in doing so makes a bold argument about how we should understand the history of scientific theories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDarwin, Charles,-1809-1882-Authorship. 0aDarwin, Charles,-1809-1882-Knowledge-Geology. 0aDarwin, Charles,-1809-1882. 0aGeologyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aGeology-Great Britain-History-19th century. 0aLyell, Charles,-Sir,-1797-1875. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAlexander von Humboldt.  aCharles Darwin.  aCharles Lyell.  aOn the Origin of Species.  aSociology of Scientific Knowledge.  aauthorship.  abiography.  acoral reefs.  aevolution.  ageology.  atheories.  atheory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106885800 cprintz978022652311840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226523255423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226523255/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles